At 86, he has governed the country for over a decade, taking over from his brother, the late Fidel Castro. Between them, the Castro brothers have spent almost 60 uninterrupted years in power on the Communist-run island, but now a non-Castro is about to take the helm for the first time since 1959. 

The cult of personality in Cuba is strong with some revolutionary leaders almost hero-worshipped. However, the next generation of leaders lack the same inspirational backstories as the Castros. And some Cubans are already turning to an unlikely place on the largely atheist island: the Evangelical church. The BBC's Will Grant is in Havana and sends this report… --BBC--